    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2901600421?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Miriam Cihodariu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Miriam Cihodariu" href="/user/show/51872363-miriam-cihodariu">Miriam Cihodariu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51872363-miriam-cihodariu?shelf=scotland">scotland</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51872363-miriam-cihodariu?shelf=wales">wales</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51872363-miriam-cihodariu?shelf=ireland">ireland</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51872363-miriam-cihodariu?shelf=england">england</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2901600421" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11881189587972292186">I got off to a slow start on this series, mostly because I was wary of Atlantis tropes and more than half of the book is very Atlantic-centric.<br/><br/>But then it got me :). Since I recently went on a tour of Scotland and finished reading Malory&apos;s collection of Arthurian legends, I was in the mood to delve deeper in this world with some high-quality fiction developing on the original mythology. Stephen Lawhead&apos;s series definitely did not disappoint.<br/><br/>What I liked most: <br/>- it&apos;s a timeless read, it can safel</span>
  <span id="freeText11881189587972292186" style="display:none">I got off to a slow start on this series, mostly because I was wary of Atlantis tropes and more than half of the book is very Atlantic-centric.<br /><br />But then it got me :). Since I recently went on a tour of Scotland and finished reading Malory's collection of Arthurian legends, I was in the mood to delve deeper in this world with some high-quality fiction developing on the original mythology. Stephen Lawhead's series definitely did not disappoint.<br /><br />What I liked most: <br />- it's a timeless read, it can safely be enjoyed by kids 12+ and it's not boring for adults either;<br />- it's so well documented: all the old named for places and rivers, along with old forms of common words and named, everything stands its ground if you do some research of your own and makes you appreciate the realism of the tales even more<br />- the parts about old 6-7th century Wales and the relationship between the Romans, the south of the wall Celts and the north of the wall tribes - they all seem super realistic</span>
  <a data-text-id="11881189587972292186" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


